<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">O</span>h happy Colorado Sunday, friends.</p>

<p>The week was short, but filled with excitement only semi-related to the weather that is mostly unfamiliar for early July. We&#8217;ve had an outbreak of tiny toads at my house, and my driveway most nights is functioning as a snail superhighway (like real snails, with shells, plump enough to be plucked for escargot if I were <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.grit.com/farm-and-garden/how-to-make-escargot-ze0z1211zsch/">brave enough and had two weeks to spend working on an appetizer</a>.)</p>

<p>The rain is to blame for all this novelty. I am a native Coloradan and by birthright have a perpetual understanding that we need the moisture. This year, there&#8217;s been so much moisture that drought has been stripped away and our wild and urban landscapes have been transformed. The greening is almost overwhelming and I know it won&#8217;t last.</p>

<p><strong>Jennifer Brown</strong> and <strong>Hugh Carey </strong>experienced similar feelings late last month, when they made <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/09/16/wild-horses-sand-wash-blm/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">a return trip to the Piceance Basin</a> to report this week&#8217;s cover story about how volunteers are working to make sure a herd of wild mustangs isn&#8217;t too large to thrive when summer conditions return to typical in northwest Colorado.</p>

