<h2><strong>&gt;&gt; Are birth control darts the solution to Colorado&#8217;s wild horse fight?</strong></h2>

</mj-text><mj-image href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/09/wild-horses-fertility-darts-colorado/" src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/HorseDart_HC_10.jpg?w=1200" padding="0px 0px 0px 0px" />
<!-- Cutline -->
<mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px"><p class="cutline">Wild mare and her foal gallop across the fields of yellow clover near Meeker. (Hugh Carey, The Colorado Sun)</p></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>In the Piceance, a geological basin rich in oil and natural gas reserves and ringed with rose-colored mesas, the land is lush. Red Indian paintbrush, blue lupine and yellow clover stand out among the sagebrush. The grass is tall and thick. And the wild horses that roam the rangeland are stout and healthy.</p>

<p>This year.</p>

<p>Next year, it could look like it did in 2021, when the ground crumbled to dust and the creeks dried up.</p>

<p>This summer-by-summer fluctuation is part of the reason that mustang advocates, mustang volunteers and the federal regulators responsible for managing the land have argued for decades about what it can handle. Standing in the Piceance this summer, among the blooming cactuses, it&#8217;s easy to believe there&#8217;s plenty of food and water for the estimated 750 wild horses living there — enough even to share with the grazing cattle whose owners lease the land.</p>

<p>But the Piceance, one of four wild horse management areas in Colorado, is supposed to have just 235 horses, according to the Bureau of Land Management. Getting to that number is expected to take another roundup and a larger investment in a fertility-control program that is now small and volunteer-based.</p>

<p>Photographer <strong>Hugh Carey</strong> and I spent a day in the basin with two women trying their hardest to support a compromise in the wild horse population problem, and saw just how hard it is to get close enough to a wild mare to shoot it with a birth-control dart.</p>

<p>They&#8217;re out there year after year, witnesses to the seasons full of wildflowers and rushing streams and the ones when the horses would die of thirst if they didn&#8217;t haul in water. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/09/wild-horses-fertility-darts-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

