<h2><strong>&gt;&gt; Fireflies are a highlight of the Colorado summer</strong></h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/DSC_0922-1-scaled.jpg?w=1200" padding="0px 0px 0px 0px" />
<!-- Cutline -->
<mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px"><p class="cutline">Butterfly Pavilion entomologist Francisco Garcia, right, holds a trap containing a firefly captured at Riverbend Ponds Natural Area in Fort Collins. His team was allowed to trap 50 insects for research. (William Allstetter, Special to The Colorado Sun)</p></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>It&#8217;s not your imagination, displaced Easterners with fond memories of summer nights lit up by the flashes of courting insects, we do have fireflies in Colorado. And now is the time to watch for them in marshy areas around the state.</p>

<p>&#8220;A lot of native Coloradans have never seen a firefly, don&#8217;t even know they exist out here,&#8221; said Beth Kittrell, a volunteer for Fort Collins Natural Areas, which has for three years run &#8220;<a target="_blank"  href="https://engage.fcgov.com/ActivityRegistration/32075c33-2b44-43ae-8eb3-8a9bc5d21d22">Light Up The Night</a>&#8221; tours of the Riverbend Ponds Natural Area during firefly season. They are now one of its most popular activities, with a long waitlist. (The next one is Wednesday and registration is required.)</p>

<p>Fireflies need a fresh, moist environment to thrive, which is why they are widespread — but also under threat — across much of the eastern United States. Fireflies <a target="_blank"  href="https://butterflies.org/colorado-firefly-watch/">also thrive in scattered oases across Colorado</a> and can be seen flashing their mating calls in wetlands for a few short weeks in June and July.</p>

<p>Fireflies were identified in 2018 near Loveland, which now has its own &#8220;Fireflies in the Meadow&#8221; programs in July, though you can go on your own at the Morey Wildlife Reserve at the western edge of the Mariana Butte golf course. Reported sightings in recent years range up and down the Front Range from Greeley to Pueblo, and in several mountain valleys near Moffat, Divide, Durango and Carbondale.</p>

<p>On a recent evening, as lightning flashed from thunderheads on the horizon, Kittrell led a firefly tour at Riverbend Ponds. From a parking lot near the Cache La Poudre River, the group headed out on a gravel path between ponds fashioned from reclaimed gravel pits, then onto a boardwalk that traverses a rich, open wetland of tall grasses, rushes and other water-loving plants. As darkness descended, the first flash appeared just off the boardwalk. Soon dozens of fireflies were flashing across the wetland.</p>

<p>&#8220;Best day ever!&#8221; exclaimed Hannah Brown, a member of a Butterfly Pavilion research team that had come to collect fireflies for an ongoing project. She was thrilled to see and enjoy the magical fireflies she first saw as a college student in New York. She was also happy to know that the research team would be able to collect its allotment of 50 fireflies on its only collecting expedition of the summer.</p>

<p>Led by Lorna McCallister, the Butterfly Pavilion team seeks to understand the lifecycle of the Colorado fireflies and to breed and raise them. Fireflies are disappearing from many of their traditional breeding grounds. In fact, a population that once lived in the <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.fcgov.com/naturalareas/finder/reservoirridge">Reservoir Ridge Natural Area</a>, west of Fort Collins, has not been seen for several years. McCallister and her colleagues hope their work will aid conservation efforts and possibly lead to reintroduction in some areas.</p>

<p>Another researcher, University of Colorado Ph.D. student Kit Lewers, set up two GoPro cameras to film the firefly display. Lewers is working in the lab of Orit Peleg, an associate professor in the BioFrontiers Institute at CU. Peleg is trying to learn how fireflies evolved their species-specific flashing patterns. She believes that the flash patterns, evolved over millions of years, might have something to teach us about effective and efficient communication. But it is more than just that.</p>

<p>&#8220;At heart, I am fascinated by these creatures and want to understand them,&#8221; Peleg said. &#8220;They are so beautiful and captivating.&#8221;</p>

<p>McCallister and the Butterfly Pavilion are also enlisting volunteers to record and share their sightings of fireflies through the<a target="_blank"  href="https://butterflies.org/colorado-firefly-watch/"> Colorado Firefly Watch</a>. On that page, they list several public locations where fireflies can be seen in Colorado. The season is rapidly coming to an end, but you may be able to see them if you get out there soon.</p>

